The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
Archives
 The City Diary
																																																																																		Pratima Naskar, 31, hanged herself on Sunday night with her dupatta at her home in Goni Gangadhar Lane, in Mahestala. Police said Pratima had written in her suicide note that her husband Anil was in an extra-marital relationship with a local girl and refused to sever ties despite her repeated entreaties. The couple have a son and a daughter. Anil has been arrested and Pratimas body sent for post-mortem.																																																		Alipore court on Monday granted bail to Barnali Sengupta, wife of Parthasarathi, a journalist. Parthasarathi and Barnali were arrested on September 17 at their Kasba residence following the unnatural death of his mother, Manju. She had allegedly been strangled and set ablaze. Barnalis lawyer Sujit Chakraborty said she had to furnish two sureties and Rs 5,000.																																																		Mohammad Moiuddin, 30, was arrested on Monday on Gas Street, in Narkeldanga, for allegedly raping a 12-year old. Police said the incident occurred on Sunday night when the girls parents were away from home. 																																																		 Schoolteacher Subhendu Sarkar was arrested in Thakurpukur on Monday for allegedly torturing his wife Ruma. Police have also arrested Subhendus father, Shyam Sunder, a retired government officer, on the same charge. Subhendu was married to Ruma in January 2006. The couple have a daughter of seven months. 																																																		Robbers took away Rs 2.5 lakh from the flat of Arvind Kumar Singh in the Narkeldanga railway quarters on Sunday night. Police said the robbery took place when Singh, an engineer, was not at home. No arrests have been made.																																																		The environment department of the state government has constituted a green award  Sherader Shera Nirmal Puja Puroshkar, 2007  to acknowledge the best of the community pujas in terms of carrying out environmental, social and related responsibilities, according to the senior law officer of the department, Biswajit Mukherjee.							TO Sagnik for organising a free health check-up camp for the under-privileged on Gandhi Jayanti
